Some students of a secondary school have reportedly unleashed mayhem on their teachers and WAEC invigilators. According to reports, students of Bright Senior High School at Akyem Kukurantumi, Ghana, attacked WAEC officials over strict invigilation in the ongoing WASSCE examinations in the country. A journalist was also beaten by the students during the unrest. They were allegedly angry about strict supervision and social-distancing protocols in the exam hall. Source By Chinyere Nwachukwu/Funmilayo Adeyemi/Jacinta Nwachukwu Abuja -   Stakeholders in the education sector on Saturday decried the ban of private school teachers from invigilating the West African Examination Council’s examinations. The stakeholders spoke in separate interviews with the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) in Abuja and Lagos on Saturday. The… April 14, 2018 In "News" The National Examination Council (NECO) will introduce Computer-Based Test (CBT) in objective papers of its subsequent examinations, says Dr Paddy Njoku, the Chairman, NECO Governing Board. Njoku made this known yesterday in Abuja during the board’s monitoring visit to the Model Secondary School, Maitama, centre of examination Senior Secondary School… June 12, 2015 In "News" The House of Representatives Committee on Basic Education and Services has appealed to the Federal Government not to cancel the forthcoming West African Senior School Certificate Examinations. In a statement by the Chairman, Prof.Julius Ihonvbere, titled: “WASSCE should not be cancelled,” on Friday, the lawmakers said stakeholders were not informed… July 10, 2020 In "News"